00:12:45,769 --> 00:12:47,870
Imagine for a second
that each marble is a species.

241
00:12:47,870 --> 00:12:50,269
Insects, birds, trees.

242
00:12:50,269 --> 00:12:52,430
Everything that makes up an ecosystem.

243
00:12:52,430 --> 00:12:55,149
One of the marbles is us, humans.

244
00:12:55,149 --> 00:12:56,900
Every time we take over an ecosystem,


245
00:12:56,900 --> 00:12:58,720
clear a forest,

246
00:12:58,720 --> 00:12:59,930
drain a swamp,

247
00:12:59,930 --> 00:13:01,170
create monocultures,

248
00:13:01,170 --> 00:13:04,000
it’s like we pull out a stick.


249
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:05,709
At first, not much happens.

250
00:13:05,709 --> 00:13:07,149
So we keep going.

251
00:13:07,149 --> 00:13:11,930
But then one marble drops:
a species goes extinct in some place.

252
00:13:11,930 --> 00:13:12,930
Then another.

253
00:13:12,930 --> 00:13:14,260
And another.

254
00:13:14,260 --> 00:13:15,770
Until you take just one more stick,


255
00:13:15,770 --> 00:13:18,830
and suddenly, nearly all the marbles
come crashing down.

256
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:22,640
Ecosystems behave
in a somewhat similar fashion.

257
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:26,710
They are remarkably resilient,
until they suddenly collapse.

258
00:13:27,475 --> 00:13:31,534
Here is an example from a place where
we’ve pushed overfishing just a bit too far.

259
00:13:31,939 --> 00:13:34,730
Suddenly this ecosystem collapsed.


260
00:13:35,180 --> 00:13:38,889
And the jellyfish population exploded
and completely took over

261
00:13:38,889 --> 00:13:41,876
and crowded out the remaining fish
and everything else.

262
00:13:44,215 --> 00:13:48,080
We humans tend to think
that we are separate from nature.

263
00:13:48,080 --> 00:13:52,900
But when oceans are empty
and forests are gone,

264
00:13:52,900 --> 00:13:56,810
when there are no insects
to pollinate all our crops,

265
00:13:56,810 --> 00:14:00,706
we human beings
come crashing down with the rest.

266
00:14:02,146 --> 00:14:09,190
We could stop the first episode here and
just deal with this one fact of mass extinction.






267
00:14:09,190 --> 00:14:11,089
And let it sink in.

268
00:14:11,449 --> 00:14:13,960
But unfortunately
there is a lot more happening.

269
00:14:13,960 --> 00:14:19,209
Life collapsing is just one of the three crises
we’ll be talking about today.





270
00:14:20,414 --> 00:14:22,514
The next crisis is pollution.


271
00:14:23,909 --> 00:14:25,710
Since the industrial revolution,

272
00:14:25,710 --> 00:14:28,010
people all over the world
have been exposed to pollution

273
00:14:28,240 --> 00:14:30,874
often without even knowing about it.

274
00:14:31,099 --> 00:14:33,659
But now it's catching up with us.

275
00:14:35,054 --> 00:14:37,435
Frank knows about his first hand.

276
00:14:37,660 --> 00:14:39,829
He lives in Memphis, Tennessee.

277
00:14:39,829 --> 00:14:42,630
In a community that's been devastated
by pollution.

278
00:14:44,339 --> 00:14:47,519
I was a typical child from South Memphis,
you know,

279
00:14:47,519 --> 00:14:50,000
growing up in the late seventies, early eighties.

280
00:14:51,139 --> 00:14:52,740
I was like the first person to have a fade.



281
00:14:52,740 --> 00:14:56,516
So I brought the fade in 1977/78
or whatever this was.

282
00:14:57,866 --> 00:14:59,668
It was really a great time.

283
00:15:00,250 --> 00:15:01,759
But in the midst of that, you started,

284
00:15:02,029 --> 00:15:06,320
we started noticing some
different things happening with mom.

285
00:15:07,490 --> 00:15:11,026
We will get pieces of her saying
and doing crazy things.

286
00:15:11,726 --> 00:15:14,026
And I remember being freaked out


287
00:15:14,550 --> 00:15:18,279
because I had heard the stories of
her mother having cancer.

288
00:15:19,153 --> 00:15:20,704
And a few years later...

289
00:15:21,360 --> 00:15:24,356
My big sister,
brain tumor, cancerous brain tumor,

290
00:15:24,356 --> 00:15:26,882
same part of the brain as my mom's.


291
00:15:27,625 --> 00:15:30,968
And then a few days later,
my mom's only remaining sister.

292
00:15:30,968 --> 00:15:34,022
She's diagnosed with brain cancer too.

293
00:15:35,902 --> 00:15:38,861
So getting back in the neighborhood
and talking to people.

294
00:15:38,861 --> 00:15:42,772
All of us are having the same stories.

295
00:15:42,990 --> 00:15:49,833
Castalia, which is right across from us,
that whole block was taken out from cancer.





296
00:15:50,794 --> 00:15:53,340
Now right here is Hamilton High School.

297
00:15:53,340 --> 00:15:56,790
And they said one time this school
was covered in arsenic.

298
00:15:58,407 --> 00:16:00,996
You can see the towers of the refinery.

299
00:16:01,520 --> 00:16:05,121
They put the refinery on the river
to dump into the river.

300
00:16:06,345 --> 00:16:11,065
And we turn to the right,
there's the Defense Depot.

301
00:16:11,414 --> 00:16:14,551
This is where they stored
the worst of the worst.

302
00:16:15,687 --> 00:16:19,045
All of this is having an effect
in black communities.

303
00:16:19,045 --> 00:16:23,656
Children with the behavior disorders,
uh, neurological disorders, all of this stuff.

304
00:16:23,656 --> 00:16:27,310
And everyone is sitting here
shrugging it off.

305
00:16:28,620 --> 00:16:32,609
What happened to Frank, his family
and his community is devastating.

306
00:16:32,959 --> 00:16:35,525
It’s beyond words.

307
00:16:35,962 --> 00:16:39,381
Pollution is everywhere,
and no one is safe from it.

308
00:16:39,949 --> 00:16:42,220
But so often,

309
00:16:42,220 --> 00:16:44,699
the worst kind of pollution
is concentrated

310
00:16:44,699 --> 00:16:47,920
where working class people
and minorities live.

311
00:16:49,449 --> 00:16:53,858
Every year, in the US,
350,000 people’s lives are cut short

312
00:16:54,339 --> 00:16:56,130
just from air pollution.

313
00:16:56,567 --> 00:16:58,969
And in Europe it’s 417,000.

314
00:16:59,669 --> 00:17:01,649
417,000 deaths!

315
00:17:03,747 --> 00:17:06,262
It's grayish.

316
00:17:06,262 --> 00:17:11,848
Even when it's sunny,
it's overcast and you can see that it's pollution.

317
00:17:12,543 --> 00:17:16,470
I mean, what we see there is what we breathe
in.

318
00:17:16,470 --> 00:17:20,084
It goes inside us, into our lungs.

319
00:17:21,640 --> 00:17:23,710
It's scary, actually.

320
00:17:24,570 --> 00:17:27,701
Pollution is a health risk multiplier.


321
00:17:28,400 --> 00:17:32,313
It increases the risk
of so many different things.

322
00:17:32,750 --> 00:17:36,855
I'm already seeing way more patients
with respiratory problems,

323
00:17:36,855 --> 00:17:41,523
like asthma and chronic obstructive
pulmonary disease, lung diseases.

324
00:17:42,884 --> 00:17:46,751
There is another form of pollution
that’s found everywhere, but even less visible.

325
00:17:48,460 --> 00:17:51,650
Something we didn't know, 50 years ago
when we started producing plastic,

326
00:17:52,100 --> 00:17:54,159
is that the plastic we throw out


327
00:17:54,159 --> 00:17:56,929
or the plastics in the clothes
we might be wearing right now

328
00:17:56,929 --> 00:17:59,570
break down into microplastics.

329
00:17:59,570 --> 00:18:02,040
Tiny, invisible bits
that are carried everywhere.

330
00:18:02,715 --> 00:18:04,460
Literally everywhere.

331
00:18:05,405 --> 00:18:09,695
Researchers have gone to
the most remote place on earth, the Arctic.

332
00:18:10,055 --> 00:18:12,167
And when they melted a gallon of ice,
they found it contains...

333
00:18:12,167 --> 00:18:13,957
Are you ready?

334
00:18:13,957 --> 00:18:17,060
53,000 particles of plastic.

335
00:18:18,265 --> 00:18:21,365
Carried for thousands of miles by the wind.


336
00:18:21,635 --> 00:18:27,165
Microplastic is everywhere,
in the ocean, in the rain, in the rivers.

337
00:18:27,546 --> 00:18:29,105
It's in your tap water.

338
00:18:29,105 --> 00:18:30,235
It's in the bottled water.

339
00:18:30,775 --> 00:18:33,490
It's been found in beer and salt.

340
00:18:34,120 --> 00:18:36,230
It's in the air we're breathing right now.

341
00:18:36,230 --> 00:18:38,515
The air you’re breathing too.

342
00:18:39,460 --> 00:18:43,400
According to researchers
at the University of New Castle in Australia,

343
00:18:43,400 --> 00:18:50,000
in one week, we eat, drink and breathe
the equivalent of one credit card in plastic.

344
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:51,905
That's 4 a month.

345
00:18:52,715 --> 00:18:55,744
It's even found in the placenta
of pregnant mothers.

346
00:18:55,744 --> 00:18:57,175
And in our bloodstream.

347
00:18:57,175 --> 00:19:01,585
Most likely there are microplastics
in your bloodstream.

348
00:19:01,585 --> 00:19:03,915
What this is doing to our health
we don't yet know.

349
00:19:04,680 --> 00:19:06,960
What we do know is
that industry experts predict

350
00:19:06,960 --> 00:19:09,130
that plastic production won't decrease,


351
00:19:09,130 --> 00:19:14,540
but most likely increase
by a factor of four in the next 30 years.

352
00:19:14,540 --> 00:19:17,890
How much plastic
will end up in our bodies?

353
00:19:17,890 --> 00:19:20,859
And plastic is just one form of pollution.


354
00:19:20,859 --> 00:19:24,959
Meanwhile we've released chemicals,
pesticides, and heavy metals everywhere.

355
00:19:25,409 --> 00:19:26,760
You've probably also read

356
00:19:26,760 --> 00:19:29,870
that our rivers, lakes, and drinking water
are full of medications

357
00:19:29,870 --> 00:19:32,350
like antidepressants and hormones.

358
00:19:32,350 --> 00:19:35,440
We know that this is doing weird things.


359
00:19:36,295 --> 00:19:39,724
Scientists have found that even in
what may look like pristine lakes and rivers

360
00:19:40,309 --> 00:19:42,155
and national wildlife refuges,


361
00:19:42,155 --> 00:19:46,594
the chemicals and medication in the water
disrupt the hormonal systems of wildlife

362
00:19:46,594 --> 00:19:49,645
and turn male fish into half female beings.


363
00:19:49,960 --> 00:19:53,255
They have eggs in their testicles.

364
00:19:53,255 --> 00:19:55,626
It's in the water we humans drink also.


365
00:19:55,626 --> 00:20:00,715
Infant boys are developing more
genital abnormalities and smaller penises.

366
00:20:01,159 --> 00:20:04,539
More girls are experiencing early puberty.


367
00:20:04,539 --> 00:20:07,620
Adult women appear to be suffering
declining egg quality

368
00:20:07,620 --> 00:20:10,940
and significantly more miscarriages.


369
00:20:11,345 --> 00:20:14,775
In men there's a boom in two-headed sperm.


370
00:20:15,585 --> 00:20:18,455
An international team, including researchers

371
00:20:18,455 --> 00:20:21,429
from the school of medicine
of Mount Sinai in New York,

372
00:20:21,429 --> 00:20:22,925
found that in just 40 years,


373
00:20:22,925 --> 00:20:27,870
the human sperm count in Western countries
went down by almost 60%.

374
00:20:28,630 --> 00:20:29,960
Following the current trend,

375
00:20:29,960 --> 00:20:35,129
the team of researchers suggested
sperm count could reach zero in 20 years.

376
00:20:37,149 --> 00:20:38,779
I don't know how this lands with you.


377
00:20:38,779 --> 00:20:41,330
But 20 years, that's exactly about the time


378
00:20:41,330 --> 00:20:44,754
that our children could want
to become parents.

379
00:20:45,114 --> 00:20:50,155
And so for me, this doesn't just feel like,
you know, some science article.

380
00:20:50,470 --> 00:20:51,590
When I look at our children

381
00:20:51,590 --> 00:20:54,640
and I don't know
what's happening in their body,

382
00:20:54,640 --> 00:20:57,910
it feels really personal and,
and disturbing.

383
00:20:59,350 --> 00:21:04,119
So we talked about life collapsing,
about pollution.





384
00:21:04,119 --> 00:21:07,789
And of course, we all know this,
it’s getting warmer.

385
00:21:08,668 --> 00:21:12,447
But before we dive in, let’s start with
a little science refresher on

386
00:21:12,447 --> 00:21:17,400
where the atmosphere is
and why it's getting warmer.

387
00:21:19,155 --> 00:21:24,275
Our planet is surrounded by the atmosphere,
a very thin layer of air.

388
00:21:24,275 --> 00:21:27,110
Incredibly thin,
but absolutely vital.

389
00:21:27,605 --> 00:21:30,658
It’s a blanket that protects us
from freezing.

390
00:21:30,658 --> 00:21:33,817
Without it, heat would simply go back
into outer space.

391
00:21:34,177 --> 00:21:36,510
Gasses in the atmosphere
let the sun rays through,

392
00:21:36,510 --> 00:21:38,150
but trap some of that solar energy.


393
00:21:38,510 --> 00:21:41,270
And that keeps us warm.

394
00:21:42,215 --> 00:21:49,830
The trouble is:
when we burn coal, oil, gas or forests

395
00:21:49,830 --> 00:21:55,770
we release huge quantities of carbon dioxide,
methane, and similar gases into the atmosphere

396
00:21:55,770 --> 00:21:58,600
which makes the blanket
get thicker and thicker.

397
00:21:59,185 --> 00:22:01,462
It's the reason you don't leave
a dog or a kid

398
00:22:01,462 --> 00:22:04,440
in a car alone on a sunny day
with the windows up.

399
00:22:04,440 --> 00:22:09,230
If the sun is shining hard, of course
you leave the windows a bit open!

400
00:22:09,230 --> 00:22:13,460
Otherwise the closed windows trap the heat
and your dog or child might die.

401
00:22:14,315 --> 00:22:16,355
That’ s what’s happening
to the earth right now…

402
00:22:16,355 --> 00:22:20,000
We are closing the windows,
and it’s getting hotter and hotter.

403
00:22:20,765 --> 00:22:22,485
With all the gas we’ve added,


404
00:22:22,485 --> 00:22:26,314
the world has become
1.1° Celsius warmer already.

405
00:22:26,539 --> 00:22:28,669
That’s 2° Fahrenheit.

406
00:22:29,029 --> 00:22:30,850
It doesn’t sound like much,


407
00:22:30,850 --> 00:22:33,850
but it turns out that
the world’s thermostat is

408
00:22:33,850 --> 00:22:36,010
really, really sensitive.

409
00:22:36,010 --> 00:22:38,130
It’s kind of like our body.

410
00:22:38,130 --> 00:22:42,280
When our body temperature increases
by 1° Celsius or 2° Fahrenheit,

411
00:22:42,280 --> 00:22:44,830
you know, we start to have fever.

412
00:22:44,830 --> 00:22:47,590
And maybe you remember
the heat dome of 2021

413
00:22:47,590 --> 00:22:49,059
when it was so hot

414
00:22:49,059 --> 00:22:51,370
that, all the way north in Canada,

415
00:22:51,370 --> 00:22:56,100
a town self-combusted
and burnt down in a day?

416
00:22:56,640 --> 00:22:59,680
Extreme weather events
have always happened.

417
00:22:59,680 --> 00:23:02,900
But now, normal is no longer normal.


418
00:23:02,900 --> 00:23:08,359
Not when a city like Houston, Texas,
has experienced a “five-hundred year flood”...

419
00:23:08,539 --> 00:23:11,130
... three years in a row!

420
00:23:11,771 --> 00:23:15,056
And do you remember these images?

421
00:23:16,181 --> 00:23:20,000
This was San Francisco,
during the day!

422
00:23:20,325 --> 00:23:24,685
This is smoke from the massive fires.

423
00:23:26,792 --> 00:23:30,780
Ashley, the family doctor in California,
was right there.

424
00:23:32,175 --> 00:23:39,299
So I was on maternity leave and
I was nursing her in the breakfast nook.

425
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:42,445
And the Paradise Fire started.

426
00:23:44,020 --> 00:23:48,919
It was like one of the
historically worst fires in California.

427
00:23:49,279 --> 00:23:51,785
The smoke was terrible.

428
00:23:51,785 --> 00:23:57,154
And I couldn't take her outside
for 13 days.

429
00:23:57,559 --> 00:23:59,789
I was bringing the air purifier
right beside her

430
00:23:59,789 --> 00:24:02,584
and trying to shut the doors of the room.

431
00:24:02,584 --> 00:24:04,735
Trying to keep her safe.

432
00:24:06,984 --> 00:24:13,800
I felt like I was seeing her future
and all of our children's future.

433
00:24:15,060 --> 00:24:16,830
It brought the climate crisis

434
00:24:17,100 --> 00:24:21,505
from that intellectual,
cerebral somewhere else, someone else.

435
00:24:21,505 --> 00:24:22,940
Not my life.

436
00:24:22,940 --> 00:24:25,404
It brought it all home.

437
00:24:25,404 --> 00:24:31,995
And you know, I was like watching it and
just tears falling onto her as I realize,

438
00:24:31,995 --> 00:24:34,010
like I've just been asleep.


439
00:24:35,720 --> 00:24:38,549
[Sirens]

440
00:24:38,549 --> 00:24:41,560
Global warming, doesn't only mean
things get warmer.

441
00:24:41,560 --> 00:24:44,175
It means weather patterns
get out of whack.

442
00:24:44,715 --> 00:24:45,755
We get floods and droughts


443
00:24:45,755 --> 00:24:48,865
that didn't used to exist
for a thousand years.

444
00:24:48,865 --> 00:24:51,445
Droughts all the way up to
Sweden and Canada.

445
00:24:51,445 --> 00:24:57,205
Floods like we've never seen in Germany,
Belgium, the UK and so many other places.






446
00:24:57,475 --> 00:24:59,814
Weather patterns are changing everywhere.


447
00:25:00,624 --> 00:25:04,370
And more and more of us are
experiencing this firsthand.

448
00:25:04,370 --> 00:25:06,809
Polls show that people everywhere,


449
00:25:07,126 --> 00:25:12,440
farmers, city folk, conservatives,
progressives, and moderates

450
00:25:12,440 --> 00:25:17,004
are now concerned or alarmed with
how the climate is changing.

451
00:25:18,174 --> 00:25:20,110
And as we said, in these films,

452
00:25:20,110 --> 00:25:22,620
we are focusing on Europe
and North America.

453
00:25:22,620 --> 00:25:26,920
But if we want to see
what the future holds for us here,

454
00:25:26,920 --> 00:25:29,529
we only need to look to
some parts of the world

455
00:25:29,529 --> 00:25:32,370
where things are already much worse.

456
00:25:33,615 --> 00:25:37,084
Take Malawi, in east Africa.

457
00:25:37,084 --> 00:25:39,785
Because of droughts, floods
and certain farming practices,

458
00:25:40,100 --> 00:25:44,405
farmers’ corn yield per acre
fell from 7 bags to below 3.

459
00:25:44,810 --> 00:25:48,105
The country can no longer
reliably feed itself.

460
00:25:49,095 --> 00:25:51,405
Put yourselves in the shoes of people there.


461
00:25:51,630 --> 00:25:56,710
Malawi contributed almost nothing,
less than 0.1%, a rounding error

462
00:25:56,710 --> 00:26:00,700
to the warming blanket,
but they are hit really hard.

463
00:26:01,330 --> 00:26:04,965
Or take Syria and its brutal civil war.

464
00:26:04,965 --> 00:26:10,585
It started in 2011, after the country suffered
the worst 5-year drought in its history.

465
00:26:11,242 --> 00:26:13,572
One and a half million farmers
had to give up their land

466
00:26:13,572 --> 00:26:17,256
and move to overcrowded cities
and find a way to scrape by.

467
00:26:18,875 --> 00:26:20,565
These droughts were devastating.

468
00:26:21,555 --> 00:26:23,900
And many analysts believe
they were a critical factor

469
00:26:23,900 --> 00:26:29,759
in sparking the mass protests
that Syria’s dictator then ruthlessly suppressed,

470
00:26:30,389 --> 00:26:33,179
leading to the terrible civil war.


471
00:26:33,899 --> 00:26:37,644
6 million people had to flee their homes
to neighboring countries.

472
00:26:38,094 --> 00:26:40,854
And one million found refuge in Europe.


473
00:26:42,069 --> 00:26:45,360
What the people in Malawi and Syria
have been through

474
00:26:45,360 --> 00:26:48,494
might just be
what we'll face in the future too.

